Homomorphic Encryption (HE) is one of the most important developments in modern cryptography because it changes a fundamental assumption that has existed for decades: traditionally, encrypted data must be decrypted before meaningful computation can occur. That requirement creates a major privacy problem in medicine, neuroscience, cloud computing, and AI systems because sensitive data becomes exposed during processing. Homomorphic encryption removes that requirement by allowing computations to occur directly on ciphertext while the underlying information remains encrypted the entire time.

In practical terms, this means a hospital, cloud provider, AI platform, or research consortium can process encrypted EEG recordings, hormone trajectories, genomic information, MRI scans, or electronic health records without ever seeing the raw patient data. Only the owner of the encryption keys can decrypt the final result.

The significance of this capability becomes enormous in healthcare because medical data is among the most sensitive categories of information in existence. EEG recordings can reveal neurological states, cognitive patterns, sleep disorders, seizure activity, emotional regulation signatures, and potentially behavioral indicators. Hormone timelines expose stress responses, endocrine conditions, and physiological regulation patterns. Genomic data contains lifelong inherited biological information. Electronic health records contain diagnoses, prescriptions, trauma histories, and personal identifiers. Traditional cloud AI pipelines require this information to be decrypted at some stage of processing, creating opportunities for surveillance, misuse, data breaches, insider attacks, or unauthorized analytics.

Homomorphic encryption changes the trust model entirely.

Instead of trusting the cloud provider, the user trusts mathematics.

At the center of homomorphic encryption is the idea that mathematical operations performed on encrypted data correspond directly to operations performed on plaintext data. If encrypted numbers are added together while still encrypted, decrypting the result produces the same answer that would have been obtained if the original plaintext numbers had been added normally.

This sounds simple conceptually, but achieving it securely and efficiently has taken decades of cryptographic research.

There are several major categories of homomorphic encryption, each supporting different levels of computational flexibility.

The simplest category is Partially Homomorphic Encryption (PHE). PHE supports only one mathematical operation. Some schemes allow repeated addition, while others allow repeated multiplication, but not both together.

One of the most famous PHE systems is the Paillier cryptosystem, which supports additive homomorphism. If two encrypted values are combined using the appropriate ciphertext operation, decrypting the result reveals the sum of the original plaintext values.

In medical contexts, PHE is useful for secure statistical aggregation. Multiple hospitals could contribute encrypted patient heart rates or blood pressure values into a shared dataset without exposing individual records. The system could compute total averages or population-level statistics while preserving patient confidentiality.

However, PHE becomes insufficient when more complex AI or machine-learning operations are required because neural networks require both additions and multiplications.

The next category is Somewhat Homomorphic Encryption (SHE). SHE supports both addition and multiplication, but only for a limited number of operations before the ciphertext becomes too noisy to decrypt reliably.

Noise accumulation is one of the defining challenges of homomorphic encryption. Every operation performed on ciphertext introduces additional cryptographic noise. Eventually, if enough operations occur, the encrypted data becomes undecipherable even to the legitimate key owner.

SHE therefore works well for shallow computations or limited inference tasks, but not for arbitrarily deep AI models.

The most advanced category is Fully Homomorphic Encryption (FHE). FHE supports arbitrary sequences of additions and multiplications, theoretically allowing any computable algorithm to operate entirely on encrypted data.

This capability is often described as the “holy grail” of privacy-preserving computation.

The breakthrough enabling FHE came from Craig Gentry’s work in 2009, which introduced the concept of bootstrapping. Bootstrapping refreshes ciphertexts during computation, reducing accumulated noise and allowing computation to continue indefinitely.

Although early FHE systems were impractically slow, modern research and engineering improvements have dramatically improved performance.

By 2025–2026, several major FHE schemes dominate medical and AI applications.

CKKS is one of the most important schemes for healthcare because it supports approximate arithmetic on floating-point numbers. Medical AI models often rely heavily on floating-point operations because physiological signals like EEG amplitudes, cortisol levels, oxygen saturation, or blood glucose values are continuous real-world measurements rather than exact integers.

CKKS allows encrypted computation on these approximate numerical values efficiently.

BFV is another major scheme focused on exact integer arithmetic. BFV is often preferred when exact precision matters, such as encrypted counting, exact voting systems, or structured categorical medical records.

