One of the most important healthcare applications of homomorphic encryption is privacy-preserving machine learning.

Traditional AI training requires pooling large quantities of patient data into centralized environments. This creates severe privacy and regulatory concerns. Hospitals are often reluctant to share data because doing so risks HIPAA violations, GDPR exposure, reputational damage, and patient distrust.

Homomorphic encryption enables collaborative AI without exposing raw records.

Imagine multiple hospitals attempting to train a cancer-prediction model. Each hospital encrypts its patient datasets locally before transmission. The centralized AI system trains directly on encrypted data. The server performing computation never sees unencrypted patient records. Only the final authorized institution can decrypt the trained outputs or model predictions.

This creates a new paradigm for collaborative medicine.

Rather than trading privacy for AI performance, institutions can achieve both simultaneously.

Federated learning already attempts to solve this problem by keeping data locally while sharing gradients or model updates. However, federated learning alone still leaks information through gradients and metadata. Homomorphic encryption adds a stronger privacy layer because even the exchanged gradients can remain encrypted.

This becomes especially valuable for rare disease research.

Rare disease datasets are often fragmented across institutions because no single hospital sees enough cases individually. Homomorphic encryption allows encrypted collaborative analysis across institutions while preventing direct exposure of patient genomes or diagnostic histories.

Genomic analysis is one of the most transformative HE applications.

A human genome contains extraordinarily sensitive information:

Disease predispositions

Inherited mutations

Familial relationships

Ethnic ancestry

Pharmacological responses


Traditional genomic cloud analysis exposes raw sequences to external providers. Homomorphic encryption allows variant analysis, mutation detection, and population comparisons while genomes remain encrypted throughout processing.

Projects like PRISM and encrypted genomic analytics initiatives are actively exploring these capabilities.

Another major application is encrypted medical imaging.

MRI, CT, PET, and ultrasound imaging increasingly rely on AI interpretation. Traditionally, uploading imaging data to cloud AI systems exposes patient anatomy and diagnostic information.

With homomorphic encryption, imaging features can remain encrypted while AI models perform inference remotely.

This has enormous implications for telemedicine and rural healthcare.

A small hospital lacking specialized radiologists could upload encrypted scans to a cloud AI provider without exposing patient identities or anatomical data.

The cloud processes encrypted tensors directly and returns encrypted predictions.

Only the hospital decrypts the diagnostic output.

