One of the most important practical aspects of homomorphic encryption is performance.

Despite enormous progress, HE remains computationally expensive compared to plaintext computation.

Depending on the workload, encrypted computation may be:

10x slower

100x slower

1000x slower


than ordinary computation.

The exact overhead depends on:

Circuit depth

Ciphertext size

Bootstrapping frequency

Multiplication count

Parameter selection


Deep neural networks remain especially challenging because they require many sequential multiplications.

Researchers therefore optimize models specifically for HE compatibility.

For example:

Activation functions may be approximated using low-degree polynomials.

Quantized networks reduce computational complexity.

Hybrid inference pipelines offload only sensitive operations into HE environments.


Hardware acceleration is becoming increasingly important.

Modern HE acceleration efforts include:

GPU acceleration

FPGA acceleration

ASIC research

SIMD vectorization

Cloud coprocessors


Libraries such as OpenFHE increasingly exploit parallel computation to reduce inference latency.

Bootstrapping performance has improved dramatically by 2026, but it remains one of the dominant computational bottlenecks.

Bootstrapping refreshes ciphertext noise, allowing continued computation.

Without bootstrapping, ciphertexts eventually become undecryptable.

Early bootstrapping operations once required minutes or hours.

Modern implementations can perform bootstrapping in milliseconds or seconds depending on configuration and hardware.

This progress is making real-time encrypted AI increasingly plausible.

However, many systems still use hybrid approaches:

Sensitive operations use HE.

Less-sensitive operations use traditional encryption.

Critical computations remain local.


This balances practicality with privacy.

Noise management remains another major engineering challenge.

Every encrypted multiplication increases noise substantially.

Developers therefore carefully design encrypted computation graphs to minimize multiplicative depth.

Medical AI models often require substantial architectural redesign to become HE-compatible efficiently.

